Instead of splitting on a random feature, GF computes {{2110.13883_FO0209||FO}} sparse random projections of the feature space and splits on that 1D projection, which minimizes the fast-BIC criterium (see below). To generate sparse projections, GF samples a random projection matrix {{2110.13883_FO0210||FO}}, where an entry {{2110.13883_FO0211||FO}} is non-zero with probability {{2110.13883_FO0212||FO}}, i.e. {{2110.13883_FO0213||FO}}, and zero otherwise. The sparsity parameter {{2110.13883_FO0214||FO}} is typically set to {{2110.13883_FO0215||FO}}. Given projection matrix {{2110.13883_FO0216||FO}}, the projected feature matrix is {{2110.13883_FO0217||FO}}, from which we can extract {{2110.13883_FO0218||FO}} one-dimensional features, which are each evaluated by the splitting criterion.